Architecture Update: Modular Design for Multi-Architecture Support
Implementation Team — Internal Memo

Why This Letter Exists
Since the initial onboarding document was written, we've done hands-on investigation with three real GGUF models. That investigation revealed something important: the assumption that naming.py would be a single flat lookup table is wrong, and acting on that assumption would produce a codebase that becomes a maintenance burden as soon as a second architecture is added.
This letter explains what we found, what the right design is, and exactly what needs to change before loader.py is written. The core functionality hasn't changed — but the structure of naming.py and the filesystem around it has.

What the Model Dumps Taught Us
Three models, three different structures
We dumped tensor names from three GGUFs. The differences were instructive:

Model
What we found
Qwen3.5-9B (hybrid)
Two distinct block types alternating every 4 layers. SSM blocks have fused attn_qkv and DeltaNet state-space tensors (ssm_alpha, ssm_beta, ssm_out, ssm_conv1d). Standard attention blocks appear only at blk.3, 7, 11... etc. Requires two separate name maps and a block-type routing function.
Qwen3-4B Q8_0
Pure transformer, 36 identical blocks, split Q/K/V, 100% Q8_0. Clean, uniform, no surprises. This is the v0.1 target.
GPT-OSS-20B Q4_K_M
Mixed quant types throughout. Not Q8_0. Deferred to v0.2 once quant support is extended.

The Qwen3.5 hybrid in particular made it clear: if you hardcode a flat dict in naming.py, adding a second architecture means editing core code. That's the wrong design. Each new architecture should be an isolated, addable file — no changes to core required.

The Design Change: Architecture Registry
What changes in the filesystem
One new subdirectory. Everything else stays the same.

gguf_lora/
├── __init__.py
├── quant.py
├── naming.py          ← registry logic + auto-detect (replaces flat dict)
├── architectures/     ← NEW
│   ├── __init__.py
│   └── qwen3.py       ← v0.1 target
├── lora.py
├── loader.py
└── writer.py

That's the only structural change. Six core files remain six core files. The architectures/ subdirectory is where all per-model knowledge lives, isolated from the pipeline logic.

What naming.py now does
naming.py no longer contains any tensor name data. It contains two things only: the registry, and the auto-detection logic that reads the architecture string from the GGUF metadata and routes to the correct map.

# gguf_lora/naming.py

from gguf_lora.architectures.qwen3 import Qwen3NameMap

ARCHITECTURE_REGISTRY = {
    "qwen3": Qwen3NameMap,
    # "qwen35": Qwen35NameMap,   # v0.2
    # "llama": LlamaNameMap,     # v0.2
}

def get_name_map(gguf_path: str):
    arch = read_gguf_architecture(gguf_path)  # reads metadata key "general.architecture"
    if arch not in ARCHITECTURE_REGISTRY:
        raise NotImplementedError(
            f"Architecture not supported. "
            f"Supported: {list(ARCHITECTURE_REGISTRY.keys())}. "
            f"See CONTRIBUTING.md to add support."
        )
    return ARCHITECTURE_REGISTRY[arch]()

The GGUF metadata already contains the architecture string — llama.cpp writes it at conversion time under the key general.architecture. No user input required. Load the file, read the key, get the right map automatically.

What an architecture file looks like
Each architecture file is self-contained. It knows everything about that model family and nothing about anything else. Here is the complete qwen3.py:

# gguf_lora/architectures/qwen3.py

ARCHITECTURE_ID = 'qwen3'
NUM_LAYERS = 36

# Q8_0 tensors — valid LoRA targets
QUANTIZED_TENSORS = {
    "blk.{i}.attn_q.weight":      "model.layers.{i}.self_attn.q_proj.weight",
    "blk.{i}.attn_k.weight":      "model.layers.{i}.self_attn.k_proj.weight",
    "blk.{i}.attn_v.weight":      "model.layers.{i}.self_attn.v_proj.weight",
    "blk.{i}.attn_output.weight": "model.layers.{i}.self_attn.o_proj.weight",
    "blk.{i}.ffn_gate.weight":    "model.layers.{i}.mlp.gate_proj.weight",
    "blk.{i}.ffn_up.weight":      "model.layers.{i}.mlp.up_proj.weight",
    "blk.{i}.ffn_down.weight":    "model.layers.{i}.mlp.down_proj.weight",
}

# F32 tensors — plain nn.Parameters, never LoRA targets
UNQUANTIZED_TENSORS = {
    "blk.{i}.attn_norm.weight":   "model.layers.{i}.input_layernorm.weight",
    "blk.{i}.ffn_norm.weight":    "model.layers.{i}.post_feedforward_layernorm.weight",
    "blk.{i}.attn_q_norm.weight": "model.layers.{i}.self_attn.q_norm.weight",
    "blk.{i}.attn_k_norm.weight": "model.layers.{i}.self_attn.k_norm.weight",
}

TOP_LEVEL = {
    "output_norm.weight": "model.norm.weight",
    "token_embd.weight":  "model.embed_tokens.weight",
}

DEFAULT_TARGET_MODULES = [
    "q_proj", "k_proj", "v_proj", "o_proj",
    "gate_proj", "up_proj",
]

That file contains everything loader.py and lora.py need to know about Qwen3. Nothing about Qwen3 lives anywhere else.

Why This Matters: The Contribution Story
The registry design directly enables the open source contribution model we want. When someone wants to add a new architecture, the contribution is completely bounded:

    • [object Object] Create 
    • Register it in the ARCHITECTURE_REGISTRY dict in naming.py (one line)
    • [object Object] Add 
    • Open a PR

No core files modified except one line in the registry. No risk of breaking existing architectures. That's a contribution someone can make in an afternoon against a model they already have — the kind of PR that actually gets opened.

Contrast with the flat dict approach
If naming.py were a single flat dict, adding Phi-3 would mean editing the core file directly.
That creates merge conflicts, risk of breaking Qwen3 support, and no clear ownership boundary.
The registry pattern eliminates all of that.

One Technical Detail: GQA Shapes
The tensor dump confirmed Qwen3-4B uses Grouped Query Attention. The shapes tell the story:

Tensor
Shape — what it means
attn_q.weight
[2560, 4096] — full query heads
attn_k.weight
[2560, 1024] — fewer key heads (GQA)
attn_v.weight
[2560, 1024] — fewer value heads (GQA)
attn_output.weight
[4096, 2560] — projects back to hidden dim

This doesn't change the name map or the LoRA injection logic — PEFT handles GQA shapes correctly. But it means the LoRA matrices for K and V will be smaller than for Q, which is correct and expected. Don't be alarmed when you see it.

